Vheadline
p2
VMusic is in the air
p3
sVnews
p4
VAssociation for Carnatic Music, a body formed in Tirupati to promote and propagate Carnatic music among the younger generation, celebrated its third anniversary at Mahati auditorium last week. The event turned out to be a three-day musical feast to the avid listeners of Carnatic music.The event started with lighting of the traditional lamp by noted artist G.Balakrishna Prasad, followed by a grand vocal recital by T.M. Krishna, Chennai. The programme started with a &#8216;kriti' Makelara Vicharamu in Ravichandrika, followed by an elaborate Ragalapana in Dhanyasi (Meenalochana). The main item of the day was Nanubrovamani Cheppave (Kalyani Raga), a composition by Bhadrachala Ramadas, followed by an elaborate manodharma. K.V. Venkatakrishna and &#8216;Mridanga Ratna' Kamalakara Rao provided effective accompaniment on violin and mridangam, while Haribabu supported on ghatam.On the second day, N.Saileswari, President of the association, explained its activities and future plans of the &#8216;Sabha'. Sri Padmavathi Mahila Viswa Vidyalayam (SPMVV) former Vice-Chancellor G. Sarojamma advised parents to get their wards acquainted with the basics of traditional music. A philanthropist Nagaraja Setty, principal of SV College of Music and Dance Ch. Prabhavathi and violinist Komanduri Seshadri gave their views on learning music. Students and upcoming artists performed the &#8216;Sri Thyagaraja Pancharatna Seva' by reciting his numbers.A violin duet by Mysore Nagaraj and Manjunath in memory of &#8216;Nada Bhagiratha' Vidwan Kotipalli Prakasa Rao, was the highlight of the third day. Memorable numbers like Idi Samayamura (Chayanata), Gnanamosagarada (Poorvikalyani) and Paramatmudu (Vagadiswari) were played in perfect sync. Kotipalli Ramesh on mridangam and B.S.Purushotham on ghatam accompanied them.The association will conduct such programmes.
